- BUN-10772: Fixes #17633
- BUN-10824: Support `import.meta.hot.accept`
- Fixes #17863
- Fixes #17965
- Fixes #17900

It may fix the following issues, but the tickets (as of writing) do not provide full reproductions.

- #17896
- #17613

This rewrites most of hmr-module.ts as well as an overhaul to HMR's bundling format. You can now `require("./esm")` just like `bun build` and `bun run` support. But if there is a top-level `await`, an error is raised.

![CleanShot 2025-03-05 at 18 10 23@2x](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2ccdec53-ef9c-441b-b049-93744021722d)

Since I had to rewrite all of the code, now was a perfect time to support `import.meta.hot.accept`

```ts
// self-accepting
import.meta.hot.accept();
import.meta.hot.accept((newExports) => {});

// accept changes from other modules
import * as foo from "./foo";
export let stateful = getStateful(foo);
import.meta.hot.accept("./foo", (newFoo) => {
  stateful.foo = newFoo;
});
```

Unlike Vite, we patch inter-module dependencies automatically, making use of this function much simpler. Maybe we disable this for self-accepting modules that pass a callback.

To make the HMR easier to use and have more "just work" moments, Bun will very aggressively DCE the import.meta.hot object in production. Most simple HMR code doesn't have to be gated behind `if (import.meta.hot)`. So the most basics like the above examples can be put at top level.

`import.meta.hot.data` will inline to `{}` in production, which allows us to
simplify the existing React template very greatly. **This change was not actually
made to the template** so that it is more clear of the two states.

```diff
-if (import.meta.hot) {
   // With hot module reloading, `import.meta.hot.data` is persisted.
+  // In production, this line minifies to `const root = createRoot(elem);`
   const root = (import.meta.hot.data.root ??= createRoot(elem));
   root.render(app);
-} else {
-  // The hot module reloading API is not available in production.
-  createRoot(elem).render(app);
-}
```

This comment details a bit about the new module format.

```
/// The conversion logic is completely different for format .internal_bake_dev
/// For CommonJS, all statements are copied `inside_wrapper_suffix` and this returns.
///
/// For ESM, this function populates all three lists:
/// 1. outside_wrapper_prefix: all import statements, unmodified.
/// 2. inside_wrapper_prefix: a var decl line and a call to `module.retrieve`
/// 3. inside_wrapper_suffix: all non-import statements
///
/// The imports are rewritten at print time to fit the packed array format
/// that the HMR runtime can decode. This encoding is low on JS objects and
/// indentation.
///
/// 1 ┃ "module/esm": [ [
///   ┃   'module_1', 1, "add",
///   ┃   'module_2', 2, "mul", "div",
///   ┃   'module_3', 0, // bare or import star
///     ], [ "default" ], [], (hmr) => {
/// 2 ┃   var [module_1, module_2, module_3] = hmr.imports;
///   ┃   hmr.onUpdate = [
///   ┃     (module) => (module_1 = module),
///   ┃     (module) => (module_2 = module),
///   ┃     (module) => (module_3 = module),
///   ┃   ];
///
/// 3 ┃   console.log("my module", module_1.add(1, module_2.mul(2, 3));
///   ┃   module.exports = {
///   ┃     default: module_3.something(module_2.div),
///   ┃   };
///     }, false ],
///        ----- "is the module async?"
```

`input_graph` is renamed to `unloadedModuleRegistry` and is now of this type:

```ts
declare const unloadedModuleRegistry: Record<string, UnloadedModule>;
declare type UnloadedModule = UnloadedESM | UnloadedCommonJS;
declare type UnloadedESM = [
  deps: EncodedDependencyArray,
  exportKeys: string[],
  starImports: Id[],
  load: (mod: import("./hmr-module").HMRModule) => Promise<void>,
  isAsync: boolean
];
declare type EncodedDependencyArray = (string | number)[];
declare type UnloadedCommonJS = (
  hmr: import("./hmr-module").HMRModule,
  module: import("./hmr-module").HMRModule["cjs"]
) => any;
declare type CommonJSModule = {
  id: Id;
  exports: any;
  require: (id: Id) => any;
};
```

## Reference Workers by Name

Use `WorkerRef` to reference an existing worker by its service name rather than by resource instance. This is useful for worker-to-worker bindings when you need to reference a worker that already exists.

```ts
import { Worker, WorkerRef } from "alchemy/cloudflare";

const callerWorker = await Worker("caller", {
  bindings: {
    TARGET_WORKER: WorkerRef({
      // reference the worker by name (not created with Alchemy)
      service: "target-worker"
    })
  },
});
```

### RPC Type

If you're using a WorkerEntrypoint RPC, you can provide its type:

```ts
import { Worker, WorkerRef } from "alchemy/cloudflare";
import type { MyWorkerEntrypoint } from "./src/worker.ts";

const callerWorker = await Worker("caller", {
  name: "caller-worker",
  bindings: {
    TARGET_WORKER: WorkerRef<MyWorkerEntrypoint>({
      service: "target-worker",
      environment: "production", // Optional
      namespace: "main"           // Optional
    })
  },
});
```

